ABSTRACT

Passing anti-drug/anti-crime legislation seems to have become an election year tradition of the U.S. Congress. On the eve of adjournment, the 99th and 100th Congresses enacted omnibus anti-drug legislation, which created new programs, significantly increased federal funding for anti-drug programs, and instituted additional criminal sanctions for drug-related crimes. To explain this phenomenon, the symbolic aspects-those directed at the public-of the congressional policy-making process which led to the enactment of the Anti-Drug Abuse Acts of 1986 and 1988 are examined. Specifically, the legislation is analyzed in terms of three symbolic components of criminal law-reassurance/threat, moral education, and providing a model for the states. This article describes how the initiation, enactment, and specific provisions of recent anti-drug and anti-crime legislation were affected by Congress’ need to: 1) reassure the public that the nation's drug problem was under control, 2) communicate an anti-Drug use message to the law-abiding and 3) provide model laws and programs for the states. The findings presented raise a number of issues and questions regarding the content and formulation of Drug and criminal justice policy, the congressional policy-making process, in general, and Congress's ability to respond effectively to national problems.
